ğŸ§± 1. Brute-force (Triple nested loops)
ğŸ” Idea:
Try all combinations of (i, j, k) such that i + j + k == n and all â‰¤ limit.
Approach :::  â€œTo start simple and ensure I understand the problem well, I used a brute-force approach. I tried all possible combinations where each child gets from 0 to limit candies, and I checked if the sum equals n. This required three nested loops â€” one for each child.â€

ğŸ‘‰ â€œThis approach is very intuitive but has a time complexity of O(limitÂ³), which is fine for small values but will time out for n or limit near 1e6.â€


â±ï¸ Time Complexity: O(limitÂ³)
class Solution {
public:
    long long distributeCandies(int n, int limit) {
        long long count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i <= limit; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j <= limit; j++) {
                for (int k = 0; k <= limit; k++) {
                    if (i + j + k == n)
                        count++;
                }
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
};
âœ… Very slow for large n and limit.
################################################################################################
ğŸ”» 2. Improved Brute-force (Two Loops + compute third)
ğŸ” Idea:
Loop for i and j, compute k = n - i - j, and check if k is within bounds.
  Approach :::  â€œNext, I realized that we donâ€™t need to loop over the third child. Once we fix the candies given to the first two children, we can directly calculate how many candies the third one must get using: k = n - i - j. So I reduced it to two loops and just checked if k is within the valid range 0 to limit.â€

ğŸ‘‰ â€œThis brings the time complexity down to O(limitÂ²) and is significantly better, but still not scalable to 10â¶ values.â€


â±ï¸ Time Complexity: O(limitÂ²)

class Solution {
public:
    long long distributeCandies(int n, int limit) {
        long long count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i <= limit; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j <= limit; j++) {
                int k = n - i - j;
                if (k >= 0 && k <= limit)
                    count++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }
};
ğŸŸ¡ Still not good for large limit, but better than 3 loops.
#################################################################################################
âœ… 3. Optimal (Two Loops Eliminated Using Math)
ğŸ” Idea:
Fix one childâ€™s candy (say i), then count valid values of j such that: ğ‘—âˆˆ[max(0,ğ‘›âˆ’ğ‘–âˆ’limit),min(limit,ğ‘›âˆ’ğ‘–)]jâˆˆ[max(0,nâˆ’iâˆ’limit),min(limit,nâˆ’i)]

You count how many values of j are valid â†’ that's the number of (j, k) pairs where j + k = n - i.
Approach :::  â€œNow I started thinking about how I could eliminate the second loop too. I noticed that for a fixed value of candies given to the first child (say i), I need to count how many valid combinations of (j, k) exist such that j + k = n - i, and both are between 0 and limit.â€

â€œThe number of such valid pairs is simply the number of integer values j such that j âˆˆ [max(0, n - i - limit), min(limit, n - i)].â€

ğŸ‘‰ â€œSo for each i, I calculate the range of valid j values and count how many values lie in that range â€” this gives the number of valid (j, k) pairs. Adding them for all i gives the total.â€

ğŸ‘‰ â€œThis reduces the time complexity to O(min(n, limit)), which is optimal for the constraints.â€
â±ï¸ Time Complexity: O(min(n, limit))

class Solution {
public:
    long long distributeCandies(int n, int limit) {
        long long res = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i <= min(limit, n); i++) {
            int remaining = n - i;
            if (remaining <= 2 * limit) {
                int low = max(0, remaining - limit);
                int high = min(limit, remaining);
                res += (high - low + 1);
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
âœ… Efficient even for n = 1e6, used in contests and interviews.
